<HEAD>Living Donor Recipient Has Follow-up Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's second recipient of a liver from a living donor underwent another operation Tuesday to remove a pocket of infection from her abdomen, officials at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a 16-month-old liver defect victim from <LOCATION> Millington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, received part of a liver Dec. 8 from her father, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a dry-wall installer. Hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said Dr. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Emond </PERSON>, a member of the original transplant team, decided the best way to deal with the small abcess was to reopen the operation incision to drain and clear the area of infection. `` She tolerated the procedure very well, and was out of the operating room in about two hours,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, adding the infection had not been life-threatening. The spokeswoman said <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> was listed in critical but stable condition after the two-hour operation, and was expected to be transferred out of the intensive care ward within several days. Also Tuesday, <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who preceded <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> as the nation's first living-donor liver transplant recipient, had her condition upgraded to serious `` She continues to progress well,'' Ms. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> was given a `` day pass'' from the hospital to visit with her parents on Christmas Day at a <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> for relatives of ailing children. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 29, an elementary school teacher who donated part of her liver to her daughter for the Nov. 27 transplant, was released from the hospital two weeks ago. The Smiths are from <LOCATION> Schertz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> is expected to leave the hospital sometime after the first of the year if all continues to go well, according to Ms. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sarina </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alyssa </PERSON> suffer from biliary atresia, a usually fatal congenital defect which is the leading cause of liver transplants in children.
