<HEAD>China Charges Five With Helping Dissidents Flee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says it arrested five <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> residents on charges of trying to smuggle dissidents out of the country and today accused a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> group of running an `` underground railroad.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> said the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alliance </LOCATION> for Supporting the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> helped dozens of dissidents flee abroad since the army crackdown on pro-democracy protests in June. Police said the arrests `` dealt a major blow to the overseas reactionary forces who attempted to use <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> as sanctuaries for criminals,'' the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said in a report Monday. The five arrests were made over the past three months, and <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> did not say why they were being announced only now. It said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will `` punish severely those who dare to plot and ship wanted criminals out of the mainland.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said repeatedly it will not allow residents of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> to interfere in mainland affairs, but this was the first time it explicitly accused the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> alliance of running the underground railroad. The alliance was founded after the June crackdown, which increased anxiety in British-ruled <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and Portuguese-ruled <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> about their return to <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> rule in the coming decade. The official <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> defended the arrests in an editorial in today's editions, saying `` <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> residents must obey Chinese laws when on the mainland.'' In excerpts of the editorial, the paper accused the alliance of smuggling abroad `` important counter-revolutionary criminals. ... The Chinese government will never tolerate such activities.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> considers ethnic Chinese from the two colonies to be <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizens and has rejected past efforts by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to intervene on behalf of arrested <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> Chinese. The arrests were likely to increase <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> fears about Chinese rule, which already have sent many in search of haven elsewhere.
