<HEAD>Selections From Beckett's Works</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Beckett, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a selection of quotations from the writings of <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>, the playwright who died Friday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` Waiting for Godot'': We are all born mad. Some remain so. Estragon: Let's go. Vladimir: We ca n't. Estragon: Why not? Vladimir: We're waiting for Godot. Nothing happens, nobody comes, nobody goes, it's awful!
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> Dies'': Death must take me for someone else. To be buried in lava and not turn a hair, it is then a man shows what stuff he is made of. To know he can do better next time, unrecognizably better, and that there is no next time, and that it is a blessing there is not, there is a thought to be going on with.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` All that Fall'': This dust will not settle in our time. And when it does some great roaring machine will come and whirl it all sky-high again.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` Endgame'': Clov: Do you believe in the life to come? <PERSON> Hamm </PERSON>: Mine was always that.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` Murphy'': There is no return game between a man and his stars.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 From `` Stirrings Still,'' <PERSON> Beckett </PERSON>'s last published work: A clock afar struck the hours and half-hours. The same as when among others <PERSON> Darly </PERSON> once died and left him. Strokes now clear as if carried by a wind now faint on the still air. Cries afar now faint now clear. Head on hands half hoping when the hour struck that the half-hour would not and half fearing that it would not. Similarly when the half-hour struck. Similarly when the cries a moment ceased. Or merely wondering. Or merely waiting. Waiting to hear.
</TEXT>
