edders </PERSON>, stepped down amid allegations that he beat his wife <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> was credited with restoring morale at the agency and spearheading a series of major investigations. In May 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> filed charges against <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, whose cooperation led to <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who in turn implicated <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> in the largest securities fraud case ever brought by the government. The scandals in recent years have forced Wall Street's big brokerage houses to re-evaluate their compliance and ethics codes and led <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to increase the penalties for insider trading.
