<HEAD>China Claims Mao Revival As Chairman's 96th Birthday Marked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> marked the 96th birthday of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> on Tuesday amid official claims that young people disillusioned with Western philosophies are rediscovering truth in the works of the late Great Helmsman. The official press says there is a quiet resurgence of interest in <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, the father of Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> who, since his death in 1976, has also been blamed for bringing great suffering to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with his radical policies. Young people, the media report, have abandoned their <PERSON> Sartre </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nietzsche </PERSON> and have returned to the works of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. College students, <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Wen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hui </PERSON> <PERSON> Daily </PERSON> said, after traveling the `` winding road'' of fascination with Western thought, `` have returned to our forefathers to ask for advice. ... Is this not a good omen?'' The implication is that college students, after the government's bloody suppression of their pro-democracy movement this year and months of heavy political indoctrination, now realize that <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> were right all along Young people questioned privately said they had heard of no one rushing out to buy `` The Selected Works of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>.'' `` <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> is a kind of cover,'' said one graduate student. `` Journalists have to perform their job, they have to write something'' and <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> is a safe subject that adheres to party line, he said. Crowds at <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s mausoleum in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, where his body lies in state, were far smaller on his birthday Tuesday than in previous years. A bitingly cold Siberian wind may have kept many away, as did the continuation of martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> that limits access to the square to those with proper IDs. One vender outside the mausoleum said 10,000 to 20,000 people a day viewed <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s body before June. Now, the number is 4,000 to 5,000 daily. The overseas edition of the official <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday reported the increased popularity of <LOCATION> Shaoshan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s birthplace in rural southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. It said <PERSON> Shaoshan </PERSON> will receive 600,000 visitors this year, up from last year but still far below the nearly 3 million pilgrims a year during <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s lifetime. The daily also said <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s 96th birthday was being marked with the release of a tape titled `` A Truly Great Man of No Equal In His Time'' on which 12 of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s poems are set to traditional music. A book chronicling <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s family line back to the Yuan Dynasty -LRB- 1271-1368 -RRB- was also published. However, a check of several bookstores found neither tape nor works by <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>. A clerk at one of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s larger bookshops said <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s works had been sold out since June, but a saleswoman at a smaller shop said, `` we have n't carried <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s works for five years.'' Another clerk corrected her, saying, `` we have n't carried them for 20 years. Every family already has his works, so there's no need to buy them.'' During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s disastrous attempt to purge the bureaucracy and restore ideological purity to the revolution, all Chinese were required to possess his `` Little Red Book'' of quotations and study from it daily. Official reports of a revival of interest in Mao have also been tempered by warnings against nostalgia for the personality cult around <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> that his successor, <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, has tried to eschew. `` Everyone knows that <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> was a man and not a god,'' the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Daily said. It quoted <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> as saying <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> was a great man and `` if it were not for Chairman <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> our country would have groped in the dark for an even longer period of time.'' But it cautioned against `` great mass fervor among young students'' for the Great Helmsman. There is little sign of that, although some Chinese embittered by the government's corruption and harsh suppression of democratic reform look back fondly on the revolutionary ideals represented by <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> in the early days of the People's Republic. `` People prefer <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> to now,'' said the graduate student. `` The present government is too corrupt. At least <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> was for the people.''
