<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government of President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> suffered an economic setback Tuesday when the Argentine currency lost 27 percent of its value against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar in a single day. At the close of the business day, foreign exchange houses offered 1,700 australs for each dollar. Last Friday, the market rate was 1,230 australs per dollar. Banks were closed Monday for Christmas. After weeks of pressure against the austral, the government Dec. 10 formally devalued the currency by 34 percent, bringing the official and free market rates briefly in parity. However, the austral plunge anew after interest rates soared as did prices and wage demands by workers. On Dec. 15, Economy Minister <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> resigned, and his successor, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, three days later freed the exchange rate and lifted most price controls. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> has struggled with the economy ever since taking office July 8. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> is <PERSON> Menem </PERSON>'s third economy minister, and <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> is the third <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> president. So far this year, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has had six economy ministers and five <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> presidents.
