<HEAD>Cuban Seeks U.N. Meeting on Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> on Tuesday requested an urgent meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to condemn <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for ordering troops to circle the Cuban Embassy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> during the hunt for Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. No meeting was scheduled during informal council consultations Tuesday night, but the question could be considered again. Cuban Ambassador <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Oramas </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliva </PERSON> made the request in his second letter in two days to <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Penalosa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. He said that people in the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> ambassador's residence in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and in the embassy were virtual prisoners At least 25 children and 30 women were being prevented from leaving, he said, calling the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action a violation of international law and infringement upon the rights of diplomatic personnel. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops surrounded the Nicaraguan and Cuban embassies in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Thursday after rumors surfaced that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> may be hiding in one of the missions. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> turned himself in Sunday to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> mission in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Last week, the council met at the request of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, which sought to condemn the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. But the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Saturday vetoed a resolution that would have deplored the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military action and demanded immediate withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces.
