<HEAD>China Blocking Meeting on Romania to Prevent Comparisons, Diplomats
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is blocking <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> debate on the revolt in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> because it fears comparisons with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s own violent encounter with pro-democracy protests, diplomats said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> put off discussion on <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> on Tuesday because of resistance by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the diplomats said, speaking on condition of anonymity. A <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said only that the Romanian question, which had been placed on the agenda, had not been taken up. There was no comment from Chinese diplomats. Weeks of pro-democracy protests in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> earlier this year were crushed by troops in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says about 300 people died, 200 of them civilians. Witnesses and Western security sources say the toll may range from 500 to 3,000. In <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, the new revolutionary government says more than 12,000 people were believed slain during a week of protests against the rule of ousted leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, who ordered troops to shoot demonstrators. Mass graves were found in the western city of <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> diplomats said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> government wants to avoid any comparison with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has reacted sharply to international criticism to its crackdown. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> diplomats familiar with council proceedings said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, with the support of some developing nations, argued that the situation in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> was strictly an internal affair and the international community should not become involved. Other diplomats argued, however, that the instability in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> threatens <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and that maintaining international peace and stability is a legitimate concern of the 15-nation <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> last week requested that the issue a statement about the crisis in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. They suggested the council could deplore the violence among the demonstrators, army and security forces and call for an orderly transition to democracy. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, however, refused Saturday to permit <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Penalosa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to read an informal statement of concern to reporters. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is one of the five permanent council members with veto power and can block a statement. A council statement requires a concensus. The five permanent members are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
