<HEAD>Summary of Events in Romania</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Romania, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of events Tuesday in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Romanian television shows tape of deposed leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Elena </PERSON>, after they were executed by firing squad for crimes against <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> They lay crumpled on the ground in front of a bullet-riddled wall. Earlier, television showed footage of the couple at what is believed to have been their secret trial. _ Romanians cheer the executions and Romanian sources say the security forces loyal to <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> are beginning to surrender en masse. _ The new revolutionary government says <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> and his security forces killed 60,000 people during his 24-year rule. Television shows what is described as a torture chamber in <LOCATION> Timisoara </LOCATION>. _ The revolutionary council names its informal leader, <PERSON> Ion </PERSON> <PERSON> Iliescu </PERSON>, a former official ousted by <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>, as chairman of the governing council It also names <PERSON> Petre </PERSON> <PERSON> Roman </PERSON>, a 43-year-old professor of hydraulic engineeering with no political background, as prime minister. _ The provisional leadership repeals travel restrictions and other hated <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> laws, lifting the dictator's orders to destroy thousands of rural villages and move the residents into the cities. It revokes family planning restrictions, rules on talking to foreigners and allows Romanians unrestricted ownership of such once-regulated items as typewriters. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> loses control of the security forces, which are put under the jurisdiction of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which controls the army. It was the army that sided with pro-democracy protesters when revolution broke out, and security forces who remained loyal to <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
