<HEAD>Yugoslav Communists Propose Ending Monopoly on Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Central Committee of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> recommended Tuesday that the party adopt a proposal to end its 45-year monopoly on power in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. The party will consider the proposal at its January congress in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>. The Yugoslav <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was the first to break with the monolithic communist bloc in 1948. But <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has been slower to adopt many of the democratic reforms now sweeping <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Secretary <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Korosec </PERSON> told the 165-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> the party is ready for competition of `` equal political partners.'' <PERSON> Korosec </PERSON> said the party will embark on reforms `` not to reject the idea of socialism, but to preserve and develop it further.'' The draft is a `` result of ambition to prove that we ... do not find ourselves at the tail of reforms in socialism,'' he said. Other political parties have already been allowed in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION>, two of the six republics in the Yugoslav federation. <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest republic, decided this month to allow other parties with some restrictions. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has a population of 23.5 million.
