<HEAD>Jews at Western Wall Celebrate Hanukkah with World via Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several thousand people at <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s Western Wall celebrated Hanukkah Tuesday via satellite with Jews in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The mostly ultra-Orthodox crowd watched quietly as prayers were chanted and the fifth candle was lighted in all five cities in the first high-tech global Hannukah ceremony. Hannukah, the eight-day festival of lights, celebrates the victory of the Jews over the Greco-Syrian kingdom in 165 B.C. The kingdom tried to impose its culture on the Jews and desecrated the holy temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> with statues of <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> gods. According to legend, when the Jews entered <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and tried to rekindle the temple's eternal flame, they found enough oil for one day, but the oil miraculously lasted eight days. To commemorate the miracle, Jews light candles at sunset for eight consecutive days. The Western Wall, where the candle-lighting ceremony was held, is the sole remnant of the second Jewish temple and the holiest site in Judaism. <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabakoff </PERSON>, a 60-year-old tourist from <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, watched one of two screens facing the Western Wall with excitement. She said she heard about the satellite ceremony in her hotel, from announcements in the streets over loudspeakers. `` I think it is wonderful that Jews feel that strongly about their faith to join together. It makes me want to cry,'' she said. The candle in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> was lighted by Ashkenazi Chief Rabbi <PERSON> Mordehai </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliahu </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s two chief rabbis. The <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> crowd listened to a speech in Yiddish from <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, by the <PERSON> Lubavitcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Rebbe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneerson </PERSON>. The rabbi's Habad movement sponsored the satellite ceremony. <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodzin </PERSON>, an 18-year-old seminary student from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, said the highlight for her was watching children in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> celebrate Hannukah. `` I think it's amazing. Look at all the people here. This one TV show is tying together the Jews from all over,'' she said.
</TEXT>
