<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUARRY HEIGHTS, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> probably went by himself to the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and decided to seek asylum after his aides abandoned him or were arrested, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. It said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was never in charge of his <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion on Dec. 20 and did not contact any of its members for fear of a trap. During the fighting, military spokesmen had said the resistance was centrally directed and <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was involved. In a brief communique released to reporters, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> gave an account of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s time after the invasion based on what it said were interviews with his cronies. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> at one point considered `` fleeing to the mountains to mount an insurgent attack, but he was concerned about his heart while living in difficult terrain without the opulent luxuries and intensive medical care'' to which he had become accustomed, according to the communique. It quoted aides who were interviewed as saying <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> wore red underwear to ward off the `` evil eye.'' The communique said that before the invasion, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had dismissed the possibility of an attack by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops and was in Colon, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, inspecting a new military facility. `` He was aware of increased <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> force activities but discounted the notion of an attack, passing the increased activity off as more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> posturing,'' the communique said. It said that about 6 p.m. on Dec. 19, he was dropped off at a <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> club in <LOCATION> Tocumen </LOCATION> near the Omar Torrijos airport. `` There he was provided a prostitute by one of his aides _ apparently a routine occurrence,'' it said. When <PERSON> Tocumen </PERSON> was attacked about 1 a.m., <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> left the club and evaded <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces by driving around <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, according to the communique. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s first telephone call after the invasion was to his mistress, <PERSON> Vicky </PERSON> <PERSON> Amado </PERSON>, and that he never tried to contact his wife, <PERSON> Felicidad </PERSON>. It said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was `` agitated'' and spent the days at various locations, mostly at the home of relatives of his private secretary, <PERSON> Marcella </PERSON> <PERSON> Tason </PERSON>. His supporters tried to make him leave town but he refused, it said. It added that at one point, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was believed to have contacted the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> ambassador and considered going to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s embassy but backed off because the compound was surrounded by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration had set a $ 1 million bounty for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> decided to go `` single-handed'' to the <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> after one of his commanders, <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Cid </PERSON>, surrendered to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <PERSON> David </PERSON>, 200 miles west of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <L