<HEAD>Police End Prison Disturbance, Free Hostages, Kill 5 Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police attacked a prison cell block controlled by jailed drug traffickers and rescued 18 hostages held for two days, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Tuesday. Six traffickers died and five hostages were injured in the bloody rescue operation Monday night. Also Monday in <LOCATION> Salgar </LOCATION>, a town 167 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, a group of unidentified men massacred six farmers, the <LOCATION> Antioquia </LOCATION> state governor's office reported Tuesday. An official communique said authorities still had not determined the motive for the mass killing, and that no arrests had been made. Right-wing death squads have killed scores of other peasants in the same part of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> the last year. Later Monday, two police officers were assassinated, apparently by members of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s largest and oldest guerrilla group in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vega </LOCATION>, a town 260 miles south of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Cauca </LOCATION> state governor's office reported The assassinations apparently were carried out by the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colombia </ORGANIZATION>, the communique said. The leftist guerrilla group has increased its activity in recent months. Last Saturday, members of the group ambushed an army patrol and killed 10 soldiers in rural eastern <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> prison takeover ended Monday when police gained the release of all the hostages, including two children. A <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the situation at <LOCATION> L