<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Taxpayers receive their annual holiday greetings from Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> starting today, as the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> mails out more than 107 million tax forms and instruction packages. The forms, which have been waiting at post offices across the nation for weeks, should be in most taxpayers' hands before Jan. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> always times the mailing, which costs $ 26 million for postage and printing, to come right after the crush of Christmas mail but soon enough to give taxpayers as much time as possible to complete their returns before the filing deadline, which falls this year on April 16. For taxpayers still reeling from the sweeping changes wrought by the 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reform </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Act </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has reassuring words: the new forms look very much like last year's forms.
