<HEAD>AP World Symposium 90s Editor's Note</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The 1980s come to an end on a crashing wave of change across the world: Communism collapsed in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and is in convulsion in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Chinese students shook <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s aging Communist establishment and while their democracy movemement was crushed it is not dead. The <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> saw an uprising of Palestinians against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The cauldron of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> boiled over. South Americans reeled in the throes of economic crises brought on by mountains of debt. And so it went across the world ... But what lies ahead for the new decade? In the following stories, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents in key areas of the world look ahead to the decade of the 1990s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Dec. 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891226-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-26-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Symposium-WesternEurope Adv31   12-26 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Symposium-Western Europe, Adv 31,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 31, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WORLD SYMPOSIUM '90s: Europe _ Merging of East and West? ^With
LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 West Europeans are looking anxiously eastward as they plunge ahead with elaborate plans for the 1990s in a climate changing so quickly that answers are coming faster than questions. Their grand design is a `` single <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' of 12 Economic Community members starting at the end of 1992, a melting away of internal barriers and a blending of policies under the umbrella of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. But after the Berlin Wall crumbled, and as a 44-year-old Iron Curtain buckles, everything from the pace of integration to the overall strategy has been thrown into doubt. Some Europeans suspect that against Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s image of a `` common European home,'' the smaller `` single <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' structure is a shaky house of cards. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> is under mounting pressure to stand down in the face of former enemies who are now acting like friends. The official view, stressed at a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> summit at <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> in December, is that a united <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is crucial to helping <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> leaders moved closer to a central bank, a common currency and uniform social benefits. They also agreed to set up a Bank of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to help newly democratic eastern neighbors. The <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> called for a flexibility yet to be defined, and most of its leaders applauded <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s plans to support a stronger <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> and to broaden <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> into a political forum for solving problems. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, speaking on a visit to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> in December, suggested a greater dialogue with the East, not only on European problems but also to ease tensions elsewhere in the world. `` As <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> changes, the instruments for Western cooperation must adapt,'' he said. `` Working together, we must design and gradually put into place a new architecture for a new era.'' Whatever shape a new <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> takes, its leaders agree, the cornerstone will be <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In many ways, the divided nation has already united. Much hangs on how this union is formalized. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> would grow from a reasonably sized <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> partner to a colossus of 80 million inhabitants with a gross national product of $ 1.4 trillion, approaching the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s. Without a separate <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> military alliance is reduced to a few satellites that are fast slipping away. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> insists that a re-united <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> would demilitarize <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and draw the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other Eastern European countries closer to the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>. But President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> maintains it is too early to predict the direction <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> now will take. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> clearly prefers separate Germanys while publicly supporting the Germans' right to settle the issue themselves. French leaders expect <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to block any formal reunification. Other <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> partners, while encouraging the lightning-fast changes, take a similar stance for varying reasons. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> fear investment and development funds they counted on will be diverted to the East. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> argues that postwar borders should remain intact. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which has resisted <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> monetary and social integration, may find an ally in a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> anxious to preserve some independence within a single <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. But Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, after an emergency summit in November, made it plain that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was not anxious for a rapid blurring of East-West lines in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` All military matters must continue to be conducted through <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact,'' she said. `` At a time of great change, it's necessary to keep the background of stability and security.'' In <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, reunification is already a dominant issue in general elections, still a year off. Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> has thrown open the door and encouraged investment to speed unification. In <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, West German officials already refer to `` the eastern part of the country.'' If <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON>'s center-right coalition stays in power, it will have a mandate to push reunification. In such circumstances, <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> is likely to have reluctant support from <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, among others. In broad terms, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s mood is buoyant. The <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> estimates put growth at 2.7 percent for 1991, higher than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would like a share of that prosperity. Some officials say the Soviets now prefer trade to domination in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. On Dec. 18, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> signed a 10-year trade pact, opening the way for a larger Western role in a changing Soviet economy. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> remarked: `` This is a result of a gigantic effort made by the peoples of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to overcome political and military confrontation, to overcome the economic division of our continent.'' In short, he said, `` the Cold War is over.''
</TEXT>
