<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 31, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP World Symposium '90s: South Pacific _ Tiny Islands Come of Age</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The idyllic <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> saw its first coups, political violence and secessionist battles in the 1980s. But in the decade ahead, the `` Century of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>'' beckons and the island states expect to have a small but assertive voice in the world. Speaking in unison across a vast expanse of water will be the voices of a new generation of post-colonial leaders with intractible problems: malnutrition, fragile economies with scant export prospects and urban unemployment brought on by villagers flocking to towns with increased expectations. `` One of the continuing difficulties of the small island states is that many will remain dependent on foreign aid, and in some respects more in the past as they continue to grapple with these problems,'' said an Australian government offiical. The decade of the 1980s saw unprecented turmoil in the region. <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> had two racially inspired military coups. Civil lawlessness in <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> claimed more than 50 lives. The capitals of <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION> suffered destructive rioting. Hostage-taking in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> triggered a bloody French assault. Added to that was a perceived Soviet military threat to the region, concern about <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s growing economic inroads and anxiety that <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> was making a foothold in an area better known for its tranquility and palm-fringed lagoons than as a political hothouse. Covering 22 percent of the world's surface, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> is home to 5 million people, excluding <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>. Environmental problems like depletion of the ozone layer over <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> and the Earth's global warming has caused serious concern in a region of low-lying atolls that could be swamped by seas swollen by melting polar ice. The future of <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> is assured a big debate as countries like <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> push for protected wilderness status against others who view the world's last great wilderness as a minerals treasure house. `` If for nothing else, that will happen because of the sheer importance of <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> in regard to the world's weather patterns,'' said the Australian official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Driftnet fishing _ the casting of huge nets over a large area of the sea to scoop up tons of fish at once _ was a problem virtually unheard of six months ago. But it moved into world forums after island governments banded together to draw up an international convention and propose <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> resolutions that forced <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to scale down the practice. The 1980s gave birth to an anti-nuclear <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and the declaration of a South Pacific Nuclear Free Zone adopted by 15 island states. `` They are increasingly becoming very effective in articulating their point of view and building up cooperation among member states, `` said the Australian official. `` It is a small, but growing voice helped by a new generation of more assertive leaders.'' Against that, he said, `` There are no new bonanzas looming that are going to provide them with any riches.'' The concept of the `` Century of the Pacific'' took a first, tentative step in 1989 when 12 major <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> countries, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, met in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, to plan the future. They agreed to meet again in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> in early 1990 and probably again in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, later in the year to plan an Asian-Pacific cooperative venture, an idea all agreed was one `` whose time has come.'' The <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> meeting brought together <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> with his counterparts from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. They represented 1.9 billion people and $ 280 billion in trans-Pacific trade, 50 percent more than trans-Atlantic trade. The meeting was described by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials as the most important economic initiative in 50 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Dec. 31</NOTE>
