<FIRST>a i BC-Symposium-Caribbean Adv31   12-26 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Symposium-Caribbean, Adv 31,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 31, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WORLD SYMPOSIUM '90s: Caribbean _ Trouble on the Horizon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, which comprises some of the world's poorest and most heavily indebted nations, faces the prospect of increasing economic and social pressures in the 1990s. Problems confronting the two dozen island states south of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> range from rising unemployment and shrinking markets for sugar and bananas to the spread of AIDS and drug trafficking. Some analysts believe the strain could be severe enough to produce a resurgence of radical politics and civil unrest. `` There is just no way for stable democracy to continue in these islands unless more jobs and income are generated,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, adviser on the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> for Gov. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. While celebrating the 500th anniversary of <PERSON> Colombus </PERSON>' discovery of the New World in 1992, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> will likely find itself still coping with the effects of events dictated far from its shores. <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> leaders have expressed concern, for example, that the Cold War thaw could divert Western investment from their region to the nations emerging from communist domination in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Likewise, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> could be forced to reduce its economic dependence on the Soviet bloc, said <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Girvan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caribbean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economists </ORGANIZATION>. `` What's happening in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is changing our external environment,'' he said. `` What's happening in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> must change the environment of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' For much of the region, one of the darkest clouds on the horizon is the proposed single European market after 1992. A unified market would lift trade barriers within the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and harmonize foreign trade agreements. Among the nations most at risk are the <LOCATION> Windward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Dominica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Grenada </LOCATION>, which together ship 240,000 tons of bananas a year to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. After 1992, they could lose preferential access to the British market and face fierce competition from more efficient banana producers elsewhere. Many also fear the loss of benefits as a result of the new U.S.-Canadian trade accord and proposed changes in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> Initiative, the program set up by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to promote U.S.-oriented economic and political development in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` The next decade is going to test the very theory that microstates can survive in a world increasingly dominated by massive trading blocs,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Birns </PERSON>, director of the Washington-based Council on Hemispheric Affairs. Propects for the sugar industry, meanwhile, are dimmed by years of sharply declining <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import quotas, low world prices and increasing reliance on corn sweeteners and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European sugar beets. <PERSON> Compton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourne </PERSON>, professor of economics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, said he thought pressure would build on <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> governments to follow through on commitments to integrate their economies and pool limited resources. But he said propects for the 1990s largely depended on the willingness of developed nations to reduce the region's debt burden and provide sorely needed investment. Analysts said the expected loss of revenue from traditional exports would probably accelerate a move into tourism, already the No. 1 earner of foreign exchange for several islands, and enhance such industries as computer data entry that use cheap, semi-skilled labor. <PERSON> Birns </PERSON> said there was a danger that environmental considerations will be overwhelmed by the rush to exploit the islands' lucrative tourism potential. Tourism is also regarded as a significant factor in the rapid spread of AIDS, prostitution and drug use throughout the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. Although conservative, pro-U.S. governments dominate the region, <PERSON> Birns </PERSON> said, `` the approaching crisis'' could give rise to radically leftist leadership and possible destabilization. If Western lending institutions such as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> force further economic austerity on such debt-ridden nations as <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, `` you're going to see an increasingly dangerous situation,'' <PERSON> Birns </PERSON> said. He added that the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> of the 1990s would figure more prominently in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy because of increased immigration and closer scrutiny of the region's role as a major drug-trafficking route and source of money-laundering through offshore banks. <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>'s perennial trouble spot, approaches the new decade at a political crossroads. Opinion is divided over whether <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s military leader, Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>, will fulfill his pledge to turn over power to a civilian government in elections scheduled for the fall of 1990. No one expects a swift solution to the country's profound economic problems.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Dec. 31</NOTE>
