<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: `Always'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It's a curious irony that the leading commercial filmmaker of the cynical 1980s is a devout romantic. Throughout his career, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> has taken a sunshiny view of the human situation. His heroes, notably <PERSON> Indiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, always triumph over insuperable odds. Life may hold its miseries, as in `` The Color Purple,'' but the struggle is always worth it in the long run. Even <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>'s space visitors -LRB- `` Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' `` E.T. The Extra-Terrestrial'' -RRB- prove benign. `` Always'' is <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>'s most romantic film yet. The new movie stems from his fondness for the happy-ending films of the 1940s, especially `` A Guy Named <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>.'' That film provides the basis for `` Always,'' which is not likely to win the hearts of hardbitten critics but should appeal to the millions who embraced `` Field of Dreams'' early in 1989. In the new version, the air war of World War II has been supplanted by the battle against devastating forest fires. The sense of jeopardy is not the same, hence the dramatic tension is diminished. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> is the hotshot pilot of the tanker bomber base, taking risks that alarm his sweetheart, <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, an air controller. He believes he is invincible, but during a daring rescue of his buddy, played by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, his plane explodes. <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> finds himself on a grassy oasis amid a burned-out forest, getting instructions from an angel _ <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON> in a white designer pantsuit. The guardian angel tells <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> his mission: to return to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> unseen and help <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> overcome her grief and pass on his flying prowess to another pilot. Enter <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a klutzy flier who needs <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON>' help but is handsome enough to sway <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>'s heart <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON> lavishes all his craft on `` Always,'' and no director makes better use of the camera. The fire scenes have a frightening immediacy, and the flying is among the best in recent times. The fault lies in the script, credited to <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Belson </PERSON> and the late <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> but seemingly the work of many hands. Consistency of tone is lacking, and the plot has certain confusions, as though important scenes had been cut. The cast performs admirably. <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> displays the solidity of <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON>, who originated the role. <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> is highly effective, especially after she drops her down-home cuteness. <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON> neatly fits his large frame into the <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond-Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> kinds of roles. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> has the looks of a'40s screen idol and is likely to become a star of the'90s. `` Always'' is a Universal-United Artists picture produced by <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. The rating is PG, probably for mild swearing and excitement. Running time: 121 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> rating definitions: G _ General audiences. All ages admitted. PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be suitable for children. PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children. R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age restrictions.
