<HEAD>$Adv 00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Forbidden Sun'' -LRB- Academy Entertainment. VHS-Beta, $ 79.95. Rated R -RRB- <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> plays a former Olympic athlete who runs a summer school for girl gymnasts on the island of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>. Among her pupils is <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>, a juvenile delinquent who wants to emulate the ancients Greeks and vault over the horns of a live bull. When one of the girls is raped, <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> uses a variation of the `` bull dance'' to get revenge. Uh huh, this film is as lame as it sounds. The suspense lasts about as long as a skip across the balance beam. The payoff at the end is meager. Filled with references to arson, bulls, rape and young women, `` Forbidden Sun'' undoubtedly has some kind of psychosexual subtext, but do n't waste your time trying to find it. By <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Great Balls of Fire'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION>. VHS-Beta, $ 89.98. Rated PG-13 -RRB- Some of the best movie biographies are films such as `` Lawrence of Arabia,'' `` Gandhi'' and `` Raging Bull,'' all carefully researched and written and based on a variety of sources. And with such standard-bearers, why does <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> continue to seek out books, usually best sellers, that give only a fragmented -LRB- and sometimes biased -RRB- account of an event or life, and rush to make movies of them? Are the creative minds of the film industry incapable of doing original research and stories? These questions come to mind with `` Great Balls of Fire,'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>'s movie on the life and times of the piano-pumping rocker <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, based on the book by <PERSON> Myra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> with <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Silver </PERSON>. <PERSON> McBride </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Baran </PERSON> did the screenplay. The movie is a kinetic romp through the early years of rock' n' roll, when <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> was King and pretenders like <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> threatened to topple him The music is non-stop fun, whether songs by Presley and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, or <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Autry </PERSON> singing `` Rudolph the Red Nosed Reindeer'' or <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> `` Baby'' <PERSON> Cortez </PERSON> stomping through `` Happy Organ.'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON> is a treat as <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. He's manic, lewd, adorable and crazy. He swaggers about with childish abandon, and dances with the piano like a careless lover. At times, though, <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON> becomes almost cartoonish in his portrayal. But that's OK, because <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> was a walking comic book. <PERSON> Myra </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Winona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ryder </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- was <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s third wife. She also was his third cousin and 13 years old when they married. He was 22. Ryder -LRB- `` Heathers'' -RRB- continues to impress with her film work. She is a great casting choice for the pubescent, pulchritudinous bubble gum-chewing <PERSON> Myra </PERSON>. She is wide-eyed and dreamy-eyed, giggly and pouty, lusty and innocent. Their wedding scene is a wonderful slice of life. Ryder stares blankly at the justice of the peace, mouth ajar like he's the purple people eater. Later, at the dinner table with her parents, she bursts into giggles knowing that she's married and they have n't a clue The year was 1958, and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> had already shot to the top of the charts with `` Whole <PERSON> Lotta </PERSON> <PERSON> Shakin </PERSON>' Goin' On'' and `` Great Balls of Fire.'' But his marriage to <PERSON> Myra </PERSON> shocked a staid post-war public, and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' career crumbled. The movie is centered on <PERSON> Myra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s relationship -LRB- it should have been titled `` <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> and Myra'' -RRB- and abruptly ends with the birth of their son, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who drowned in a swimming pool when he was 3. The late <PERSON> Trey </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> co-stars as <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> launched Presley and others. <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> is deliciously self-righteous as <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>' cousin and boyhood buddy, TV evangelist <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> `` Great Balls of Fire'' is a harmless piece of entertainment for a Saturday afternoon. It's fun to watch, especially <PERSON> Quaid </PERSON>'s gymnastics and clownish grimaces But the movie lacks authenticity; it seems to be laughing at itself and at the era it purports to chronicle. There's also an element of racism. A scene at a black nightspot, for example, depicts black patrons as lewd animals doing bumps and grinds, and crawling over each other in the most suggestive ways. By <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editor </ORGANIZATION>.
